  doi = {10.1029/2006JF000664},
  abstract = {The ice sheet-ice shelf transition zone plays an important role in{\textbackslash}ncontrolling marine ice sheet dynamics, as it determines the rate{\textbackslash}nat which ice flows out of the grounded part of the ice sheet. Together{\textbackslash}nwith accumulation, this outflow is the main control on the mass balance{\textbackslash}nof the grounded sheet. In this paper, we verify the results of a{\textbackslash}nboundary layer theory for ice flux in the transition zone against{\textbackslash}nnumerical solutions that are able to resolve the transition zone.{\textbackslash}nVery close agreement is obtained, and grid refinement in the transition{\textbackslash}nzone is identified as a critical component in obtaining reliable{\textbackslash}nnumerical results. The boundary layer theory confirms that ice flux{\textbackslash}nthrough the grounding line in a two- dimensional sheet- shelf system{\textbackslash}nincreases sharply with ice thickness at the grounding line. This{\textbackslash}nresult is then applied to the large- scale dynamics of a marine ice{\textbackslash}nsheet. Our principal results are that ( 1) marine ice sheets do not{\textbackslash}nexhibit neutral equilibrium but have well- defined, discrete equilibrium{\textbackslash}nprofiles; ( 2) steady grounding lines cannot be stable on reverse{\textbackslash}nbed slopes; and ( 3) marine ice sheets with overdeepened beds can{\textbackslash}nundergo hysteresis under variations in sea level, accumulation rate,{\textbackslash}nbasal slipperiness, and ice viscosity. This hysteretic behavior can{\textbackslash}nin principle explain the retreat of the West Antarctic ice sheet{\textbackslash}nfollowing the Last Glacial Maximum and may play a role in the dynamics{\textbackslash}nof Heinrich events.},
